newsitem.title: SINGAPORE: Asia Product Swaps - Gas oil up in volatile trade.
newsitem.headline: Asia Product Swaps - Gas oil up in volatile trade.

text.p: Singapore gas oil swaps firmed in active volatile trading late afternoon Thursday peaking at $26.65 per barrel on profit-taking but gave up half its gains on expectations of aggressive physical offers, traders said.
"Trading was volatile as the Wall Street players bought the market up but it quickly disapeared after these buyers withdrew," one trader said.
Brokers said the buying from the Wall Street players were mostly to capture earlier profits.
Traders said the swaps market may fall again to below $26.00 per barrel as was the case on Wednesday when the physical players come out to offer later in the day.
"Physical offers are likely to be at an aggressive level similar to yesterday," one trader said.
Offers for physical cargoes were seen down to $24.80 per barrel loading in mid-February on Wednesday.
February fuel oil swaps extended its strengthen on expectations of renewed physical buying interest.
The market was last quoted at $101.50/$102.50 with March quoted at $102.50/$103.50 per tonne, up about $5.00 from Wednesday.
February swaps traded at $100.00, $102.75 and $103.00 per tonne earlier today.
The market rebounded after several physical buyers emerged late Wednesday when offers fell to a low of $93.00 per tonne free-on-board Singapore.
One 20,000-tonne cargo traded at this level between a European major and a Dutch trader but other buyers at this level failed to secure any cargoes.
But others said the rebound might be short-lived as supplies remain healthy.
